<h1>To Robert Cary &amp; Company</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Gentn</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Mount Vernon 20th June 1762</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>The other side contains a Copy of my last,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> since which I have received from Messrs Hill Lamar &amp; Hill a pipe of Wine price in Madeira 30.16 Sterl: for which they value upon you.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> I have also received advice of Seventy Sacks of Salts coming into Rappa. River from Mr Backhouse on my Acct. Mr Lewis who gives this Information has promised to send it round but the expences &amp; trouble attending this is so great that I had almost as soon have Goods in any part of Great Britain as in any River except the one on which I live.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>We have had one of the most severe Droughts in these parts that ever was known &amp; without a speedy Interposition of Providence (in sending us moderate &amp; refreshing Rains to molifie &amp; soften the Earth) we shall not make one Oz. of Tobacco this Year. Our Plants in spite of all our efforts to the contrary are just destroyed, &amp; our grain is absolutely perishinghow it may be in other parts of the Country I can not positively say, yet I have heard much complainingshoud it be with Reason of which you can guess by the letters of your different corrispondants I am perswaded you will be in no haste to dispose of the Tobo I have put on board the Unity, shoud it get safe to hand, with the Convoy with whom (the Chesterfield) She is to Sail sometime this Month<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0004-ptr">4</a>The London fleet is not yet arrived nor have we any Accts of it. I shall take the first oppertunity that offers of writing to you again on these heads, In the mean time I remain Gentn Yr Most Obedt Hble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0083-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Book ]">ALB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 This was sent by the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Alexandria</span> to Glasgow.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p><a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0080" class="document">GW wrote Cary on 3 June</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0002">2</a>
 
   <p>GW recorded in his diary on 13 June that he received a Pipe of Wine (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald Jackson and Dorothy Twohig, eds. &lt;i&gt;The Diaries of George Washington&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 197679. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diaries</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-01-02-0007-0006#GEWN-01-01-02-pb-0300" class="document">1:300</a>). See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0065" class="document">Hill, Lamar, &amp; Hill, 28 Feb. 1762</a>, and notes.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>John Backhouse was a Liverpool merchant involved in the Virginia trade. His ship, the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Marlborough</span>, William Quinney master, entered the Rappahannock River in May 1762. Mr. Lewis is undoubtedly Fielding Lewis who lived in Fredericksburg on the Rappahannock. GW did not receive the salt at Mount Vernon until 21 Aug. (ibid., 305).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-07-02-0083-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>GW was shipping twenty hogsheads of tobacco in the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Unity</span>. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0067" class="document">GW to Cary, 16 Mar. 1762.</a> The <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Chesterfield</span>, a man of war, was sunk in the Bahama
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-07-02-pb-0141">[141]</span>
Straits in June when participating in the expedition against Havana (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-07-02-0099&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-07-02-0099-fn-0006#GEWN-02-07-02-0099-fn-0006" class="document">GW to Cary, 30 Sept. 1762, n.6</a>).</p>

</div>
</div>
